<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Purpose: To demonstrate the design flaws and over-consolidation of functions on raids to a select few classes (sometimes referred to as “The Holy Trinity”), and the adverse impact this has on player morale and game balance.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Assumptions</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
We must make several assumptions before proceeding. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Firstly</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, that the game EverQuest is unbalanced at the high-end. Balance means that each class should have a meaningful and productive way to contribute to a group, or raid. Many classes do not, or their methods of contributing are not in the same league as the other classes’ methods, or are extremely situational.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Secondly</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, that Verant Interactive has a desire to fix these balance issues.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Thirdly</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, that the players have a desire to see these issues fixed.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Summary of Argument</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
The extremely specialized classes, namely Cleric, Wizard, and Warrior have too much going for them. They are too specialized, the cleric especially. The drawbacks that these classes have in a group situation do not balance out their extreme necessity and utility in a raid setting, where these drawbacks are rendered moot. You therefore have a few classes holding all the cards, with the other classes left to fill out auxiliary roles, minor utility functions, or in extreme cases, give their mana away outright to classes who can use it better.<br>
<br>
Some of these abilities must be distributed out to other classes, for the sake of balance at the high end. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Protection of the Glades (Druid) should be given a Hitpoint boost to bring it in line with Group Aegolism. Clerics have enough going for them already, they already have the best heal and resurrection in the game, they do not also need the best hp buffs.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Druids and Shamans should see a moderate increase in their healing power to help balance out the massive dependency on Complete Healing seen in the end-game. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Druids should receive a resurrection spell at level 60 giving 90% of experience back at a relatively high mana cost (1000 sounds right). Call it Tunare’s Rebirth, it is to allow druids to resurrect in situations where clerics are unavailable.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Paladins and Shadowknights should be given a defensive discipline in the 50s to compensate for over-reliance on the Warrior’s /disc defensive in the end-game. <br>
<br>
There is no reason a Paladin or Shadowknight should not be able to fill in for a Warrior in an emergency without expending all the clerics’ mana keeping them alive. They are defensive tanks after all, as defined by Verant themselves. A discipline to allow them to mitigate 30% of all incoming melee damage, or giving them the warrior’s /disc evasive would help enormously.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Magicians cannot realize their full potential as a class until Pet issues are addressed, and their role as nukers on raids is defined. <br>
<br>
Right now, far too many raid-level mobs resist magician direct damage spells to allow them to be a viable damage-dealing class, so they are forced to summon mod rods over and over to give to Wizards and Clerics. Any class that is forced to give their mana away to other classes is severely unbalanced and needs immediate attention. Are they nukers? Are they primarily a pet class? Are they a utility class? These questions must be answered decisively and a real answer brought forth to address this class’ concerns. Already Magicians have one of the highest attrition rates in the game. They feel worthless on raids, not because they are, but because they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> percieve</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> themselves to be. Much the same as Necromancers, this is the result of creating a class whose purpose is to be a mana whore. It is not fun to have other people play the game for you, which is what giving your mana away amounts to.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Wizards are out damaging Necromancers over long (10 minute+) fights. This simply should not be the case, regardless of DoT stacking issues. Necromancers should see a moderate (20%) increase in their damage over time to compensate.<br>
<br>
A wizard’s strength lies in their ability to deal out massive damage quickly, and a necromancer’s to deal out massive damage if given enough time. With their epic’s Rune effect, a stack of peridots, and a modrod2 magician (since they have no other role on a raid), the Wizard’s mana regeneration is much higher than a Necromancer’s, allowing them to keep up a relatively obscene damage output in excess of the Necromancer stacking all his best DoTs. Add to this the proliferation of wizard right-click nuke items (Rend robe from Xygoz, Conflag robe from Velketor, etc) and you begin to see the wizard’s encroachment on the Necromancer’s mainstay – sustained damage over time. The Wizard epic rune should be changed not to absorb modrod2 damage to prevent mudflation in this area.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Necromancers remain a class whose role is ill defined in the raid situation. They are relatively balanced in normal, grouping play, but suffer somewhat in raid situations, in part because of the lack of direction in the class.<br>
<br>
It has been said by Abashi that the Necromancer class was a mistake, due to their inability to balance it properly. It had no concrete defined role like the Cleric or Wizard, and no necessary utility in a group such as an Enchanter. Part of fixing Necromancers involves fixing technical issues, such as DoT stacking among multiple necromancers, pet pathing and aggro issues, and mobs who resist lifetaps outright; but it also requires giving the class a concrete foundation to build upon. Are necromancers a pet class? Are they a DoT class? Are they a utility class? These questions are mutually exclusive for the necromancer – currently it is a mix of all three, which lead to this problem in the first place. The raiding game is about specilization, and the obvious course for the necromancer should be specialization in damage over time. To that end, their DoT lines should be enhanced as outlined above, and the spells Infusion and Trucidation should have their component cost reduced or eliminated altogether.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Enchanters should have the amount of hate induced by the Tashan line lowered extensively. This serves no purpose but to aggravate them, in that they often end up dying for casting this one spell. The spell must be cast anyway, and is unresistable, so there is no harm in letting them live to actually see the fight. Letting them die only serves to increase downtime needlessly.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Rogues, Rangers, Shamans, Bards, and Monks are all relatively balanced classes now, so no fixes are suggested for them, though that is not to say they do not have issues worth addressing. Beastlords are not finished, so any suggestions will have to wait to see what Verant has in mind for the class.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Closing</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
EverQuest was designed, from the beginning, around the idea of a small group setting, and were balanced as such. This provided for dungeon crawls, social interaction among a small group, and easy adventuring. Unfortunately, the small group setting of six people does not scale well to a raid setting of 30 or more.<br>
<br>
Raiding was not planned for EverQuest, that much is obvious. It was tacked on as an afterthought. More attention was given to this aspect of the game with the Kunark and Velious expansions, but it was never truly balanced. As the primary melee classes became more and more powerful with each expansion, and support classes beefed up to keep them alive, the caster and auxiliary classes remained relatively static. <br>
<br>
Verant has not yet recognized the core design flaw of EverQuest: Namely, putting most of the required functions for a raid into the hands of a few classes, usually three or four. Which three or four has changed over the past few years, but the problem remains. Distributing raiding power out to more classes, and fixing the classes who need to be fixed, will only improve the game as a whole in the long run, and will actually reduce the dependency on the “Main Tank” system which Verant says it wants to steer players away from.  <br>
<br>
To balance this game may indeed require a rebuilding of the foundation upon which it was laid. Yes, that may mean (gasp) nerfs, and some mudflation, but in the end, fixing this game requires addressing its core problems, and gently trotting around trying not to step on anyone’s toes is only going to lead to a false sense of accomplishment. Verant has not yet begun to scratch the surface of game balance, and it can only get uglier from here on in. It must, though, because this game is worth fixing, and worth being enjoyably played by all classes, not just the three or four favorites of the year.<br>
<br>
- DS <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/upulid.showPublicProfile?language=EN>pulid</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/communtychest.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/30/02 6:18:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23539.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Essay: Where did they go wrong?</span><hr size=1> Just scanning through, you expect paladins/shadow knights to be able to resemble something close to a warrior while STILL casting @#%$ loads of spells? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/upooh123.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pooh123</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/30/02 6:21:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23539.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Essay: Where did they go wrong?</span><hr size=1> Great post.  You hit on many problems for the level 60 game.  Most classes are ok to 55.  Its 55+ and mainly level 60 where things go wrong.<br>
