<br>
Does the Paladin have a role in high-end encounters?  Yes, often positioning and timely LHs on a MT.  The group heal alone is valued in many encounters greatly.  Defensive to tank?  My lord that would be a kick in the nuts to Warriors.  They certainly solo well for AA and get useful skills from it generally.<br>
<br>
Ok, next the Shadowknight.  A little tougher here, they can sometimes be needed to split specific areas (rarely) and can be excellent transition tanks due to extremely good aggro gathering techniques.  They are amazing TMers on the way to a site and can also provide nice functions in exp groups.  Defensive would again massively overbalance them and yet perhaps they could use a little more raid functionality.  Again though, they can solo well at points in their careers and pay for it to some degree.<br>
<br>
Hrm, Rangers?  Just about set at 60 in my book.  They are behind Monks and Rogues in damage from melee but not so far behind that they are not contributers.  Buffs alone make it nice to have one but stacking issues limit it somewhat.  Perhaps archery changes will overpower them in times to come.  Excellent AA gatherers also.<br>
<br>
Monks?  Well, they are needed in many situations and rarely unliked in any.  Good damage, excellent skillset and relatively unreliant on maintenance.  Excellent AA soloers and good group contributers make them a favorite all round.  /shrug Stonestance and the best aggro control makes them a good choice on any raid, even if not performing pulls.<br>
<br>
Rogues?  Well, frankly I am biased of course.  We contribute damage, much like a willful DoT.  We do it in good quantities and we can, if well played, do so in a variety of circumstances.  We do need upkeep in terms of AE healing, Rampage avoidance and solid emergency healing/rezzes but we do provide more punch per player than any other melee class.  Poisons and trap disarming/ door duty add some utility.  Poison especially has potential, although it is pretty weak at the moment.  We are, of course, pretty poor AA soloers but still do well in duos and trios so I can ignore that.  Our actual class AA is awfully weak though.<br>
<br>
Warriors.  They have troubles of their own.  Although a myriad of casting items are in the game, they still need to deal with basic day-to-day needs.  In the right arena, they are the gods we all love them as.  The suckers of damage, attention and still good offensive powerhouses.  Now, there is a world between the MAIN TANK of a guild (well, hopefully several) and the average attendant Warrior.  The former often is a golden child (and rightly so for a guild that likes to win) and the latter is a poor damage add in many scenerios.  Well, in ring events and such the latter shines sometimes and in exp groups both are great to have.  AA soloing is a cakewalk for GTMs and is generally still possible for offtank warriors.  They are all well-liked folks I've found.<br>
<br>
